            "type": "FAQ",
            "question": "How can I handle my toddler’s tantrums? ",
            "created_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:38",
            "updated_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:40",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>Children are scared and out of control when they have a tantrum.  During this intense time (screaming, wailing, falling onto the floor, etc.), reasoning with your child will not help, and punishing her will only make tantrums more frequent and intense.  You can reassure your children that you are there and will help them calm down.  You know your children best: perhaps you sit with them or bring them a favourite stuffed animal to hold.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>Perhaps you remind them of some ways that they have learned to calm themselves. Never leave your crying child alone. Stay calm and close to your child. This shows that you understand and can handle whatever their emotions are. Say: “It is OK to be sad, to be angry, to be afraid. I will be here for you.” Finally, talk with your health provider if tantrums are new, intense, and challenging to manage, especially with an older child. </p>",
