            "type": "FAQ",
            "question": "Should I give my child rewards for good behavior?",
            "created_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:35",
            "updated_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:38",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>What often happens is that children learn to behave well only to get a prize! Your children listen because they will get something, not because they understand why they need to behave (the rule or limit). You also teach that the behaviour (for example, cleaning up) must be unpleasant since you “have to be rewarded” for doing it. It’s best to avoid too much use of rewards.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>Your attention and praise are important to your child, and much of the time these are enough motivation. As children get older, they may also be motivated by observing the effect of their positive behaviour on others. For example, you can say, “Look how happy your little sister is. You made her happy by giving her that toy when you were finished playing with it.”</p>",
