            "type": "FAQ",
            "question": "How can I stop my child from biting?",
            "created_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:27",
            "updated_at": "Mon, 11/29/2021 - 17:29",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>When children begin to get teeth, that is sometimes when they will experiment with biting-even when nursing! If that is the problem, you can slip a finger in, press, and firmly say, “no biting! that hurts mama!” Your baby does not know that it hurts. Somewhat older children, age 1 or 2, may bite another child if frustrated about something. Again, it is important to firmly stop the behaviour while saying, “No! Biting hurts!”</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>You can then tell the children what you would like them to do in the future. Comforting the child who is bitten is also important. Usually, older preschool children do not bite others. If your child is very easily frustrated and has other behaviour or developmental challenges (such as avoiding social connections or being unable to use language at age 3-5), do talk with your health provider about your concerns.</p>",
            "chatbot_subcategory": 110131,
