            "updated_at": "Fri, 11/26/2021 - 10:32",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>Mastitis is most common in breastfeeding women. It's symptoms often come on quickly and include a swollen area on your breast that may feel hot and painful to touch, the area may become red, and you might feel a burning pain in your breast that might be constant or only when you breastfeed. You can also experience some nipple discharge, which may be white or contain streaks of blood. You may also get flu-like symptoms, such as aches, a high temperature, chills and tiredness. </p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>Contact your doctor and use medications against infection, pain and fever on the doctor's advice. If you are breastfeeding, continue to breastfeed - start feeding with the sore breast first. Express milk from your breast in between feeds and massage your breast to clear any blockages – stroke from the sore area towards your nipple to help the milk flow. Also, rest and drink lots of fluids.</p>",
