            "question": "What can I do to help my child if he is being bullied by another child?",
            "created_at": "Tue, 11/23/2021 - 17:40",
            "updated_at": "Fri, 11/26/2021 - 10:20",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>If your child is being hurt, physically or emotionally, by another child, it’s important to help stop the bullying. Children’s feelings of self-esteem and security suffer when other children reject and hurt them. Yes, many pre-school children yell at and even hit other children as they learn how to get along. You can help your child learn other ways to handle conflicts. But some children, for many reasons, may “pick on” another child, teasing, making hurtful comments about another child’s behaviour, appearance, race, or ability. Your child may be excluded from playing with some children for reasons like this.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>If bullying happens in school, alert school authorities so you can plan the action together. If bullying happens in your own community, you may be able to spend time with the group of children and prevent it before it gets out of hand. Are there activities your child and the bullying child might enjoy together? Are there other children to play with? Can you help your child learn coping strategies--depending on her age, walking away, telling the bully to stop, finding a grownup who can help, and more.</p>",
