            "type": "FAQ",
            "question": "How can I stop my child from putting things in her mouth?",
            "created_at": "Tue, 11/23/2021 - 17:40",
            "updated_at": "Fri, 11/26/2021 - 10:20",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>Babies and toddlers love to explore with their hands. They will pick up objects and put them in their mouth to learn about the objects. Your job is to be sure that the objects you child can reach are clean and safe for your child to put in his mouth. Do not allow your child to hold small objects that she might swallow or choke on. Even fruits like grapes should be cut into smaller pieces. Do not allow your child to chew on toys that have paint that is flaking as it may contain poison.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>Look around your home to be sure that your walking baby cannot reach dangerous small objects. Of course, also be sure that the objects your child puts in her mouth are clean. If you do these things, your child can chew and explore many interesting objects. Talk to your child about these objects: “Oh, that is a big red cup! Do you like to chew on the handle?” In all these ways, you’re helping your child learn.</p>",
