            "type": "FAQ",
            "question": "How do I protect my child from abuse?",
            "created_at": "Tue, 11/23/2021 - 17:40",
            "updated_at": "Fri, 11/26/2021 - 10:20",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>Abuse may be physical (hitting, slapping), emotional (shaming, making fun of a child’s appearance or behaviour), or sexual (inappropriate intimate touching). All are harmful to a child’s sense of safety and security and have major influences on development. Although most adults can be trusted with a child, abusers may be community members, babysitters, educators, family members, or others in a child’s life. If you develop a close, trusting relationship with your child, your child will probably tell you if something happens that makes her feel uncomfortable. Make it clear to your child that his body belongs to him and it is not okay for others to touch it in ways he does not want.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>It might happen that another family member uses harsh punishment with your child. It is important to discuss discipline with everyone in the family and get agreement about avoiding harsh physical punishment and emotional abuse. You can talk about the negative effects of harsh discipline, shaming, and other behaviours on children’s development.</p>",
