            "question": "Will my child be affected if witnessing family violence?",
            "created_at": "Tue, 11/23/2021 - 17:40",
            "updated_at": "Fri, 11/26/2021 - 10:19",
            "answer_part_1": "<p>Domestic violence has many ways of affecting all the members of the family. If you are in a domestic violence situation, you need to know that this is not your fault, and you can find it difficult to give the love and attention your child needs. Children often know that family violence is going on between their parents. And even if they don’t see it, hear it or experience it directly, they’re still affected by it. Also, seeing the effects of violence is traumatic for your children. Growing up with family violence can affect children and their development in the short and long term. Children exposed to family violence might have behaviour problems like aggression, lack of emotional control and disobedience.</p>",
            "answer_part_2": "<p>If you are experiencing domestic violence, and if you or your children are in immediate danger, call the police. With help, you can limit the effects of family violence on your children. You can be the parent you want to be and help your children grow into resilient adults who can have positive relationships. If you’re experiencing family violence, there are people out there who understand and can help you and your children.</p>",
